00:06:26.900 --> 00:06:29.640
So I want to conclude this part of
my presentation with an overview

00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:32.240
of the App Store editorial process.

00:06:32.400 --> 00:06:35.840
First and foremost,
our selections are based on

00:06:35.840 --> 00:06:38.120
quality and quality alone.

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:41.230
We do not accept money for paid
placement in the App Store.

00:06:41.240 --> 00:06:46.640
We've never accepted a single penny
and we have no plans to do so.

00:06:47.220 --> 00:06:51.820
The process of choosing apps to feature
is separate from the app review process.

00:06:51.980 --> 00:06:55.580
Apps are approved or rejected based
on their adherence to our publicly

00:06:55.990 --> 00:06:58.590
available App Store review guidelines.

00:06:58.650 --> 00:07:01.930
Just because your app is approved,
however, does not mean that your

00:07:01.930 --> 00:07:03.220
app will be featured.

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:09.100
We consider apps from all 24 categories
with a particular focus on new apps or

00:07:09.150 --> 00:07:12.130
evergreen apps with significant updates.

00:07:12.250 --> 00:07:15.640
And then lastly,
while newly approved apps are added

00:07:15.720 --> 00:07:19.280
to the store on a continual basis,
new featured content is published

00:07:19.440 --> 00:07:24.930
by our team on a weekly basis,
typically Thursdays Pacific time.

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:27.520
So that's the App Store overview.

00:07:28.250 --> 00:07:30.790
The next thing I'd like to dig
into are some best practices

00:07:30.870 --> 00:07:32.660
to help you be successful.

00:07:32.660 --> 00:07:36.270
And the first one we'll talk
about is your App Store presence.

00:07:36.370 --> 00:07:41.120
This is your app name, your icon,
your screenshots, your description,

00:07:41.230 --> 00:07:42.800
and your keywords.

00:07:43.030 --> 00:07:45.910
These are things that if you're
heads down in development

00:07:45.920 --> 00:07:49.170
are very easy to overlook,
but they're not difficult to do well

00:07:49.170 --> 00:07:51.170
with a little time and attention.

00:07:51.370 --> 00:07:54.990
So to help explain what I mean here,
let's use the popular music

00:07:55.070 --> 00:07:58.060
identification app Shazam as an example.

00:07:58.140 --> 00:08:00.130
First, the name Shazam.

00:08:00.220 --> 00:08:04.960
It's unique, it's short, it's memorable,
and there's no keywords or

00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:07.140
descriptives attached to their name.

00:08:07.170 --> 00:08:10.330
And the icon,
it's beautifully designed and

00:08:10.330 --> 00:08:14.460
instantly recognizable by a
user on their home screen.

00:08:15.310 --> 00:08:20.300
Next, let's take a look at Shazam's
current screenshots in the App Store.

00:08:20.490 --> 00:08:25.210
Your screenshot should tell a story and
you should avoid distracting graphics or

00:08:25.330 --> 00:08:30.080
text overlaid on top of your screenshots
because your App Store presence is in

00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:34.090
many ways your first introduction to our
customers of your brand and your product.

00:08:34.150 --> 00:08:37.130
So Shazam, their first screenshot.

00:08:37.190 --> 00:08:39.760
Identify music in as
little as one second.

00:08:39.790 --> 00:08:44.060
It's very clear, it's very concise,
and it gives the core function.

00:08:44.060 --> 00:08:45.280
It explains the core
function of your app.

00:08:45.300 --> 00:08:48.550
It's the core function of
the Shazam app to customers.

00:08:48.550 --> 00:08:53.330
The next screenshot shows you what a song
looks like after it's been identified.

00:08:53.460 --> 00:08:56.280
You see the artist name,
you see the track title,

00:08:56.290 --> 00:08:59.900
you see the artwork,
and you see a download on iTunes link.

00:08:59.950 --> 00:09:03.920
The last two screenshots for Shazam
point out important features of the app.

00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:06.980
The explore screenshot with the
thumbnails overlaid on top of

00:09:07.110 --> 00:09:10.140
the map indicate that users can
find popular tracks by region,

00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:12.900
and on the right,
real-time top tracks indicate that

00:09:13.110 --> 00:09:15.000
users can find popular tracks by region.

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:16.730
It's self-explanatory.

00:09:16.770 --> 00:09:20.100
Explain to the user that they
can discover tracks popular

00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:23.390
across the entire Shazam system.

00:09:23.620 --> 00:09:27.140
So next, let's take a look at
Shazam's app description.

00:09:27.220 --> 00:09:30.700
Shazam recognizes music and
media playing around you.

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:34.000
Tap the Shazam button to
instantly match and then explore,

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:35.160
buy, and share.

00:09:35.160 --> 00:09:37.350
You can Shazam as much as you want.

00:09:37.380 --> 00:09:40.680
So this is taken from Shazam's
product page in the App Store.

00:09:40.680 --> 00:09:43.580
And you can see it's
optimized for device,

00:09:43.580 --> 00:09:45.540
where our customers shop.

00:09:45.620 --> 00:09:47.870
App Store customers are not
shopping on the desktop.

00:09:47.950 --> 00:09:50.840
They're shopping on the iPhone,
the iPod Touch, or the iPad.

00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:53.480
And it's clear and concise.

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:57.060
They avoided listing all the
accolades that their app has received.

00:09:57.150 --> 00:10:00.880
And they take advantage of those
first three or four lines to explain

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:03.100
in simple terms what their app does.

00:10:04.800 --> 00:10:07.140
Next, let's take a look at some keywords.

00:10:07.180 --> 00:10:10.630
I can't share with you exactly
what Shazam's keywords are

00:10:10.630 --> 00:10:13.330
because they're confidential,
but let's look at some sample

00:10:13.330 --> 00:10:16.600
keywords for a music app to help
you understand the difference

00:10:16.600 --> 00:10:18.470
between bad keywords and good ones.

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:25.470
So, music, music discovery, track, song,
album, albums, and iTunes.

00:10:25.480 --> 00:10:27.340
These are not very good keywords.

00:10:27.340 --> 00:10:29.530
So, first, music.

00:10:29.540 --> 00:10:34.020
If you don't need the category name
that your app resides in as a keyword.

00:10:34.020 --> 00:10:37.320
Next,
you see album and albums are repeated.

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:38.980
Our system handles plural.

00:10:38.980 --> 00:10:42.650
So, by inputting album as a keyword,
we would cover albums.

00:10:42.660 --> 00:10:47.500
And then iTunes is not a good keyword
for Shazam because it's only okay

00:10:47.500 --> 00:10:50.880
to use the name of a third party in
your keywords if your app uses an

00:10:50.880 --> 00:10:53.100
API provided by that third party.

00:10:54.780 --> 00:10:57.560
So here's a much stronger set
of keywords for a music app.

00:10:57.610 --> 00:11:04.370
Artist, album, song, track, discovery,
new, streaming, and lyrics.

00:11:04.640 --> 00:11:05.870
So that's your App Store presence.

00:11:05.940 --> 00:11:09.730
Your name, your icon, your screenshots,
your description, and your keywords.

00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:12.680
Again, these are not things
that are hard to do well.

00:11:12.690 --> 00:11:15.810
You just need to give them
a little time and attention.

00:11:16.490 --> 00:11:18.560
So next, business model.

00:11:18.600 --> 00:11:20.580
How do you choose the right
business model for your app?

00:11:20.770 --> 00:11:24.110
The first thing I want to talk
about is build a universal app.

00:11:24.190 --> 00:11:26.400
And I can imagine that
you might be questioning,

00:11:26.400 --> 00:11:28.100
well, isn't this a product decision?

00:11:28.170 --> 00:11:29.240
How is this a business decision?

00:11:29.240 --> 00:11:32.380
Well, it's absolutely a business
decision for a number of reasons.

00:11:32.380 --> 00:11:38.690
First, our customers love the convenience
of being able to download one binary

00:11:39.060 --> 00:11:44.490
that works on all of their devices,
as shown in this animation here.

00:11:46.180 --> 00:11:49.510
And looking back at the pie chart,
breaking down the

00:11:49.510 --> 00:11:52.690
App Store catalog by content type,
while we see growth in

00:11:52.700 --> 00:11:55.250
all of the key metrics,
catalog size,

00:11:55.490 --> 00:11:59.900
downloads and sales for iPhone apps,
iPad apps and universal apps,

00:11:59.950 --> 00:12:02.880
by far we see the highest
growth for universal apps.

00:12:02.880 --> 00:12:07.130
And the data shows that customers
are not inclined to purchase two

00:12:07.130 --> 00:12:09.900
separate versions of the same product.

00:12:10.940 --> 00:12:13.160
So next, choosing the right business
model for your product.

00:12:13.160 --> 00:12:17.070
So there's not a single prescription
that I can stand up here and say that

00:12:17.190 --> 00:12:20.500
applies to everybody in this room,
every product that you're building.

00:12:20.500 --> 00:12:23.360
But I want to leave you with
some key takeaways that will

00:12:23.360 --> 00:12:25.000
help you make a good decision.

00:12:25.550 --> 00:12:27.660
So here are three of the
potential business models

00:12:27.660 --> 00:12:29.260
available to you in the App Store.

00:12:29.260 --> 00:12:32.590
On the left you see free apps,
which are typically ad supported

00:12:32.590 --> 00:12:36.000
or support external services
like brick and mortar stores.

00:12:36.830 --> 00:12:40.640
We see a lot of developers
taking their ad supported app and

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:43.000
adding a remove ads in app item.

00:12:43.010 --> 00:12:46.150
And the key takeaway here is
that does not make your app

00:12:46.220 --> 00:12:48.000
a freemium business model.

00:12:48.580 --> 00:12:51.560
I'll spend some time talking about
freemium in just a few minutes,

00:12:51.560 --> 00:12:52.790
but just keep that in mind.

00:12:53.330 --> 00:12:56.000
Next we have traditional paid apps.

00:12:56.610 --> 00:12:59.940
There's a lot of chatter in the
blogosphere these days that the market

00:12:59.940 --> 00:13:02.000
for paid apps on the App Store is dead.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:05.430
And I can tell you as someone who
looks at this data every single day,

00:13:06.070 --> 00:13:07.500
that's completely not true.

00:13:07.500 --> 00:13:10.400
Paid apps still represent
a very significant portion

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:11.970
of the App Store business.

00:13:11.990 --> 00:13:16.000
There's no shortage of customers who
are willing to pay for the premium

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:20.140
experience and actually prefer
the premium experience where they,

00:13:20.140 --> 00:13:23.030
for a single purchase price,
they get your entire app's

00:13:23.050 --> 00:13:24.500
features and content.

00:13:25.240 --> 00:13:27.930
And then lastly we have
what we call Paymium.

00:13:27.930 --> 00:13:31.690
Paymium is a model where the parent
app is paid and there are in-app

00:13:31.910 --> 00:13:36.250
skews for additional features,
content, services that give you an

00:13:36.250 --> 00:13:39.440
opportunity for ongoing monetization
after that initial purchase.

00:13:39.490 --> 00:13:43.000
Paymium is an excellent model,
especially for those developers

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:48.480
who've been asking for a path to
paid upgrades from the App Store.

00:13:49.240 --> 00:13:51.230
So next I want to spend some
time talking about freemium.

00:13:51.350 --> 00:13:55.650
Freemium is a big buzzword in
the App Store world these days.

00:13:55.740 --> 00:13:57.730
Lots of press written about it.

00:13:57.810 --> 00:14:00.650
And I want to give you some key
takeaways to make sure you make the

00:14:00.750 --> 00:14:04.680
right decision if freemium is the
model that you're going to pursue.

00:14:05.180 --> 00:14:06.800
So let's start with the definition.

00:14:06.930 --> 00:14:11.440
Freemium is a business model where a
product or service is provided for free,

00:14:11.650 --> 00:14:14.050
but money is charged
for advanced features,

00:14:14.360 --> 00:14:16.510
functionality, or virtual goods.

