00:15:55.060 --> 00:15:55.060
So first, what are your target
market's expectations?

00:15:55.060 --> 00:15:55.060
What I mean by this is don't try to
fit a square peg into a round hole

00:15:55.060 --> 00:15:55.060
from a business model perspective.

00:15:55.060 --> 00:15:55.060
Don't have a business model
that's inconsistent with what

00:15:55.060 --> 00:15:55.060
your target market might expect.

00:15:55.060 --> 00:15:55.060
So let's take an aviation app,
for example.

00:15:55.060 --> 00:15:55.060
If you're building an app to
replace the heavy briefcases,

00:15:55.060 --> 00:15:58.240
that pilots have been carrying
onto planes for decades,

00:15:58.250 --> 00:16:02.550
the pilot's expectation is that
they're not going to be prompted to

00:16:02.670 --> 00:16:07.280
pay for every different route or every
different emergency procedure or every

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:09.080
time there's an update to the content.

00:16:09.080 --> 00:16:13.480
The expectation of a pilot for
that type of app is they'll pay

00:16:13.480 --> 00:16:17.020
one price and they will get full
access to all of the content,

00:16:17.020 --> 00:16:19.160
features, and services in that app.

00:16:19.190 --> 00:16:25.040
In contrast,
if you're building a cloud storage app,

00:16:25.040 --> 00:16:28.900
there is a target market expectation
for users of cloud storage services that

00:16:29.290 --> 00:16:35.040
some amount of storage and some basic set
of features will be available for free.

00:16:35.040 --> 00:16:38.310
And if you use that storage up or
you want more comprehensive features,

00:16:38.310 --> 00:16:39.760
you'll be prompted to pay.

00:16:39.760 --> 00:16:44.780
So there is a freemium model
does fit with the expectations of

00:16:44.940 --> 00:16:46.630
users of cloud storage services.

00:16:46.630 --> 00:16:55.020
