you may be collecting personal

01:15:48.740 --> 01:15:51.030
information from your customers
who have chosen to share

01:15:51.040 --> 01:15:53.670
this information with you,
and you can download these

01:15:53.670 --> 01:15:55.080
reports using opt-in.

01:15:55.650 --> 01:15:59.760
Finally, you'll indicate the date range,
and this is the exact date for

01:15:59.770 --> 01:16:01.960
the report you wish to download.

01:16:01.960 --> 01:16:05.100
This field is optional,
and if you do not indicate a date,

01:16:05.120 --> 01:16:08.550
we'll just provide you with the
latest available report for the

01:16:08.550 --> 01:16:10.490
parameters you've indicated.

01:16:10.520 --> 01:16:14.010
Similarly, this is the command for
the payment reports,

01:16:14.110 --> 01:16:17.050
and you'll start by
entering the same vendor ID,

01:16:17.050 --> 01:16:20.760
but for the payment reports,
you need to include two leading

01:16:20.760 --> 01:16:23.020
zeros in front of your vendor ID.

01:16:23.020 --> 01:16:23.940
Then, since the payment reports
are not available,

01:16:24.040 --> 01:16:25.340
you'll need to include two leading
zeros in front of your vendor ID.

01:16:25.340 --> 01:16:28.640
Finally, you'll indicate the
reporting region code,

01:16:28.640 --> 01:16:31.790
and if you need to access a
list of these region codes,

01:16:31.790 --> 01:16:35.660
there is one available in the
Payments and Financial Reports user

01:16:35.660 --> 01:16:37.380
guide in iTunes Connect.

01:16:37.450 --> 01:16:40.080
And the report type is
always going to be DRR,

01:16:40.080 --> 01:16:43.670
which is the standard report
type for the payment reports.

01:16:43.680 --> 01:16:47.880
And finally, you'll enter the fiscal
year and fiscal period.

01:16:47.880 --> 01:16:51.120
If you need to access a copy
of Apple's fiscal calendar,

01:16:51.260 --> 01:16:55.320
there is one available in the
Payments and Financial Reports model.

01:16:55.320 --> 01:16:57.910
module on iTunes Connect.

01:16:58.090 --> 01:17:00.220
So that's auto-ingesting your reports.

01:17:00.230 --> 01:17:03.910
And the second area of automation
I want to cover is Apple's command

01:17:03.910 --> 01:17:06.200
line tool called Transporter.

01:17:06.410 --> 01:17:11.100
Transporter allows you to automate
the delivery of your metadata,

01:17:11.100 --> 01:17:14.570
and it gives you the ability to
integrate with your own content

01:17:14.570 --> 01:17:16.640
management system if you have one.

01:17:16.650 --> 01:17:20.700
We recently introduced the ability
to deliver your rights and pricing

01:17:20.700 --> 01:17:22.600
changes through Transporter.

01:17:22.640 --> 01:17:28.520
You can request catalog reports,
and you can deliver your app metadata,

01:17:28.530 --> 01:17:32.460
which can be extremely helpful
when localizing your app.

01:17:32.470 --> 01:17:35.880
This brings me to the next
topic of localization setup.

01:17:35.900 --> 01:17:40.520
We've been talking about how you
should think global and be local.

01:17:40.550 --> 01:17:45.060
And you know that the App Store is
in 155 countries worldwide,

01:17:45.070 --> 01:17:51.360
and we offer you 28 languages for setting
up localizations with your metadata.

01:17:51.370 --> 01:17:54.860
We highly recommend using
professional localization resources.

01:17:54.860 --> 01:17:57.000
As Alex mentioned earlier.

01:17:57.020 --> 01:18:00.360
And we advise against using
automated translation services

01:18:00.360 --> 01:18:04.360
you might find on the web,
as they may translate your content,

01:18:04.380 --> 01:18:07.260
but don't fully localize it
to be culturally relevant.

01:18:07.450 --> 01:18:11.560
We also encourage you to localize
your app wherever possible.

01:18:11.560 --> 01:18:15.300
Alex showed a great example of Evernote,
where they localized everything,

01:18:15.300 --> 01:18:17.040
including their screenshots.

01:18:17.040 --> 01:18:22.690
And we know that this can be a lot of
fields to enter into iTunes Connect,

01:18:22.740 --> 01:18:25.380
but it's really important to do so.

01:18:25.440 --> 01:18:30.200
And that's why the XML feed
can be very helpful as well.

01:18:30.200 --> 01:18:33.340
Before I go into detail about that,
I do want to point out one other

01:18:33.430 --> 01:18:35.560
thing about localization setup.

01:18:35.570 --> 01:18:38.910
And that's that you are required
to submit your app for review

01:18:38.930 --> 01:18:41.140
when you add new localizations.

01:18:41.190 --> 01:18:43.680
So just make sure that you
leave enough time for the review

01:18:43.770 --> 01:18:46.940
process if you do wish to add
new localizations for your app.

01:18:47.030 --> 01:18:49.790
So for those of you who wish
to cut down on the repetitive

01:18:49.790 --> 01:18:53.530
actions that localizing can bring,
we encourage you to adopt the

01:18:53.530 --> 01:18:57.580
automated process of XML feed delivery.

01:18:57.590 --> 01:19:02.660
And the steps for using Transporter
and the XML feed are fairly simple.

01:19:02.670 --> 01:19:07.420
You can start by looking up your existing
metadata from the Apple database.

01:19:07.450 --> 01:19:11.740
And that will provide you with your
current app metadata in the format

01:19:11.740 --> 01:19:14.460
that it will need to be uploaded.

01:19:14.490 --> 01:19:17.800
Then you can make any necessary changes.

01:19:17.810 --> 01:19:22.100
And after making your changes,
you can run Transporter in verify mode,

01:19:22.130 --> 01:19:27.060
which allows you to check your changes
against our XML specifications.

01:19:27.090 --> 01:19:29.090
Then you can upload your content.

01:19:29.220 --> 01:19:32.840
And it's ready to be delivered
with your next update.

01:19:32.850 --> 01:19:37.100
You will still need to create your
new app versions in iTunes Connect.

01:19:37.100 --> 01:19:39.680
And you'll want to monitor
your state transitions,

01:19:39.680 --> 01:19:41.840
as this cannot be done
through Transporter.

01:19:41.880 --> 01:19:43.880
And I'm not going to walk through a demo.

01:19:43.920 --> 01:19:47.410
But I do want to point you to some of
the documentation available in the Manage

01:19:47.410 --> 01:19:49.820
Your Apps module of iTunes Connect.

01:19:49.830 --> 01:19:55.330
And I want to encourage you to check out
the WWDC session video from this year

01:19:55.330 --> 01:19:57.940
called What's New in iTunes Connect.

01:19:57.960 --> 01:19:59.440
They go in a little bit more detail.

01:19:59.440 --> 01:20:02.940
And they do a full end-to-end
demo of what this looks like.

01:20:02.940 --> 01:20:05.620
So if you're interested in
watching this session video,

01:20:05.620 --> 01:20:07.790
you can access it from
the developer portal.

01:20:07.980 --> 01:20:11.180
And we know that once you've set
up localizations in iTunes Connect,

01:20:11.180 --> 01:20:14.620
you like to see what this looks
like for your customer on the store.

01:20:14.710 --> 01:20:17.830
Because we get a lot of questions
about what this looks like.

01:20:18.130 --> 01:20:21.920
One thing I want to point out,
this is the Pages app for an example.

01:20:21.930 --> 01:20:25.700
And we get a lot of questions about the
list of languages that appears in the

01:20:25.700 --> 01:20:28.900
information section on the app page.

01:20:29.010 --> 01:20:32.090
This list of languages is not
the list of languages you've

01:20:32.390 --> 01:20:34.320
set up in iTunes Connect.

01:20:34.370 --> 01:20:38.630
This list of languages comes from
the lproj folder in your binary and

01:20:38.770 --> 01:20:43.410
is meant to be the languages that
you have localized your app into for

01:20:43.410 --> 01:20:45.590
when the customer has downloaded it.

01:20:45.880 --> 01:20:49.600
The localizations that you set up
in iTunes Connect are automatically

01:20:49.600 --> 01:20:53.900
displayed on the App Store based on the
customer's OS language and storefront.

01:20:53.970 --> 01:20:57.780
And they'll automatically display here.

01:20:57.820 --> 01:21:00.820
So just to take a look at what
a couple different localizations

01:21:00.910 --> 01:21:06.220
look like on the App Store,
here are a few examples.

01:21:06.230 --> 01:21:09.710
And you can see how great
this looks for the customers.

01:21:13.830 --> 01:21:17.190
I'd like to leave you with a few
tips and tricks that will help you

01:21:17.190 --> 01:21:20.050
run your business more effectively.

01:21:21.160 --> 01:21:28.940
Tip number one is regarding viewing
your localizations on the device.

01:21:28.970 --> 01:21:31.540
We just saw what this
looks like on the desktop,

01:21:31.560 --> 01:21:34.540
but it can be a little bit trickier
to view this on the device.

01:21:34.620 --> 01:21:37.940
So I'll walk you through how
to change your iOS language

01:21:37.940 --> 01:21:40.290
and storefront on the device.

01:21:40.540 --> 01:21:43.440
You'll start by entering
multitasking mode in order

01:21:43.440 --> 01:21:46.090
to quit out of the App Store.

01:21:46.590 --> 01:21:53.290
Next, you'll go to General in your
settings and tap International.

01:21:53.400 --> 01:21:55.770
Then tap Language.

01:21:56.760 --> 01:22:01.490
And then this is where you can select the
iOS language that you wish to change to.

01:22:01.800 --> 01:22:05.230
For this example, I'm choosing Chinese.

01:22:05.350 --> 01:22:08.790
So select the language, then tap Done.

01:22:10.250 --> 01:22:13.060
After that,
you'll go back to the App Store,

01:22:13.100 --> 01:22:16.340
and if you're logged into
your personal iTunes account,

01:22:16.370 --> 01:22:19.520
you'll want to sign out,
and then you'll tap the

01:22:19.520 --> 01:22:21.710
Sign In button again.

01:22:22.570 --> 01:22:26.500
Here you can see that the language
has started to change to Chinese.

01:22:26.540 --> 01:22:30.980
And I don't personally speak Chinese,
but I know that the third line here is

01:22:30.980 --> 01:22:33.920
the option to create a new Apple ID.

01:22:33.930 --> 01:22:36.000
And this is where the trick comes in.

01:22:36.000 --> 01:22:39.000
You don't actually have
to create a new Apple ID,

01:22:39.040 --> 01:22:41.340
but you will start
walking through the flow.

01:22:41.420 --> 01:22:44.570
So tap the option to
create a new Apple ID.

01:22:44.770 --> 01:22:47.500
And then you'll be prompted
to select a storefront.

01:22:47.640 --> 01:22:50.230
This is where you can select
the territory that you wish

01:22:50.230 --> 01:22:51.960
to change your store to.

01:22:51.970 --> 01:22:55.700
And for this example, I'll choose China.

01:22:55.700 --> 01:23:00.690
At this point, you can tap cancel to
exit out of the flow.

01:23:01.480 --> 01:23:04.840
Once you exit out of the flow,
your storefront will automatically

01:23:04.840 --> 01:23:07.640
change to the territory you've selected.

01:23:07.780 --> 01:23:10.720
So now that we're in
the China App Store with

01:23:10.720 --> 01:23:15.200
our iOS set to Chinese,
if we search for the Pages app,

01:23:15.200 --> 01:23:18.800
we'll see the localization
set up for Pages.

01:23:21.370 --> 01:23:26.240
Tip number two is regarding
tracking your customer reviews.

01:23:26.470 --> 01:23:30.840
Alex talked about how important tracking
your reviews can be for your business.

01:23:30.840 --> 01:23:33.130
And while you can do
this on the App Store,

01:23:33.130 --> 01:23:36.620
we also encourage you to check
this out on iTunes Connect.

01:23:36.620 --> 01:23:41.310
This page can be located
from the app summary page.

01:23:41.310 --> 01:23:45.300
And the great thing about viewing
your customer reviews in iTunes

01:23:45.300 --> 01:23:48.810
Connect is that you can easily toggle
between the different territories.

01:23:48.990 --> 01:23:51.180
Since customer reviews are specific
to each of the different territories,

01:23:51.180 --> 01:23:51.180
you can easily toggle between
the different territories.

01:23:51.220 --> 01:23:57.040
And you can access and
subscribe to an RSS feed,

01:23:57.040 --> 01:24:01.480
which allows you to receive instant
feedback when customers post new reviews.

01:24:01.480 --> 01:24:05.230
And tip number three is our
advice for scheduling a sale.

01:24:06.800 --> 01:24:09.940
The App Store is a global
marketplace and we operate in

01:24:09.940 --> 01:24:11.840
different international time zones.

01:24:11.860 --> 01:24:16.410
What this means is that pricing and
availability changes happen at different

01:24:16.460 --> 01:24:20.940
times in different countries in
different time zones across the globe.

01:24:20.940 --> 01:24:25.730
And it's what we call a rolling price
and availability setting because

01:24:25.780 --> 01:24:30.560
the change begins propagating in
one area of the world and rolls

01:24:30.690 --> 01:24:33.060
across over a period of time.

01:24:33.060 --> 01:24:35.620
So to illustrate this,
let's take a look at a map.

01:24:35.620 --> 01:24:40.060
And I'll use a price
change as an example.

01:24:40.220 --> 01:24:45.570
Let's say my app is paid and I wish
to run a 24-hour sale where customers

01:24:45.570 --> 01:24:47.970
can download my app for free.

01:24:48.290 --> 01:24:52.370
When the change begins,
the app will first fall to free in the

01:24:52.370 --> 01:24:58.880
New Zealand and South Pacific region,
followed by the Asia Pacific region.

01:24:59.180 --> 01:25:04.500
Then, Australia, Russia, India,
and the Middle East.

01:25:04.560 --> 01:25:08.480
Next, Africa, Europe, and Latin America.

01:25:08.530 --> 01:25:13.110
And finally,
the change will happen in North America.

01:25:14.470 --> 01:25:18.190
And because of this rolling schedule,
we recommend that if you

01:25:18.190 --> 01:25:22.150
wish to run a 24-hour sale,
that you actually set it up for

01:25:22.150 --> 01:25:24.240
three days in iTunes Connect.

01:25:24.390 --> 01:25:28.240
This will ensure that the change
will fully propagate for a full

01:25:28.240 --> 01:25:31.160
24 hours in each territory.

01:25:31.640 --> 01:25:34.980
And just to show you what this
looks like in iTunes Connect,

01:25:34.980 --> 01:25:40.440
you can see here that I've set the change
to begin on the 10th and end on the 13th.

01:25:40.480 --> 01:25:42.640
So that concludes our session for today.

